{"cursor":"16470","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Surface plasmon resonance' (SPR) is the collective oscillation of valence\nelectrons in a solid stimulated by incident light. The resonance condition is\nestablished when the frequency of light photons matches the natural frequency of\nsurface electrons oscillating against the restoring force of positive nuclei.\nSPR in nanometer-sized structures is called 'localized surface plasmon\nresonance'.\n\nSPR is the basis of many standard tools for measuring adsorption of material\nonto planar metal (typically gold and silver) surfaces or onto the surface of\nmetal nanoparticles. It is the fundamental principle behind many color-based\nbiosensor applications and different lab-on-a-chip sensors.\n","linknr":266,"url":"Surface_plasmon_resonance","recorded":1362510039,"links":29,"instances":["colloid","waves","chemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Electromagnetism","Nanotechnology","Spectroscopy","Biochemistry methods","Biophysics","Forensic techniques","Protein-protein interaction assays"],"headings":["Explanation","Realization","Applications","Examples","Magnetic plasmon resonance","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d5/Surface_Plasmon_Resonance_%28SPR%29.jpg/400px-Surface_Plasmon_Resonance_%28SPR%29.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Otto-schema.png/220px-Otto-schema.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/SPR-schema.png/220px-SPR-schema.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/c/b/dcbffcc1dec91c29537c9a015a03f117.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/5/0/c50b9e82e318d4c163e4b1b060f7daf5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/7/2/b72bb92668acc30b4474caff40274044.p